{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01SMiZyZi2afxQK4wqMcRcXC","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# LTL Reactive Synthesis Expert Knowledge\n     2→\n     3→## Problem overview\n     4→\n     5→**Reactive synthesis**: given an LTL specification over input and output signals, construct a controller (Mealy/Moore machine) that satisfies the spec for ALL possible input sequences, or determine that no such controller exists (unrealizable).\n     6→\n     7→**Dual optimization goal**:\n     8→1. Determine realizability status for as many instances as possible (both realizable and unrealizable count)\n     9→2. For realizable instances, minimize AND gate count in the AIGER circuit encoding\n    10→\n    11→## Available primitives\n    12→\n    13→| Tool | Purpose | Analog in MaxSAT |\n    14→|------|---------|-------------------|\n    15→| `syfco` | Parse TLSF files → LTL formula, inputs, outputs | wcnf_parser |\n    16→| `ltl2tgba` / `autfilt` | LTL → automaton conversion, automaton manipulation | SAT solver call |\n    17→| PySAT + CaDiCaL | SAT encoding for bounded synthesis | Core-guided MaxSAT |\n    18→| `ltlsynt` | Complete synthesis tool (baseline to beat) | RC2 |\n    19→| Custom Python | Game solving, strategy extraction, circuit optimization | Local search |\n    20→\n    21→## Key algorithmic approaches\n    22→\n    23→### 1. Automaton-based pipeline (standard approach)\n    24→1. Parse TLSF → LTL formula + I/O signals\n    25→2. Convert LTL to universal co-Büchi automaton (UCW) or deterministic parity automaton (DPA)\n    26→3. Build 2-player parity game from automaton\n    27→4. Solve game (Zielonka's algorithm)\n    28→5. Extract winning strategy → Mealy machine → AIGER circuit\n    29→\n    30→### 2. Bounded synthesis (SAT-based)\n    31→- Encode \"exists k-state controller satisfying spec?\" as SAT\n    32→- Try k = 1, 2, 4, 8, ... until SAT or timeout\n    33→- Directly finds minimal-state controllers\n    34→- Best for small specs where automaton blows up\n    35→\n    36→### 3. GR(1) fragment\n    37→- Specs of form (∧ GF(a_i)) → (∧ GF(b_j)) with safety/justice conditions\n    38→- Polynomial-time synthesis (no automaton construction needed)\n    39→- Many SYNTCOMP instances are GR(1) — identify and exploit this\n    40→\n    41→### 4. Safety reduction\n    42→- Some liveness specs can be reduced to safety via bounded lookahead\n    43→- Safety games are simpler (reachability/safety, no parity conditions)\n    44→\n    45→### 5. Circuit minimization\n    46→- After finding a correct controller, minimize the AIGER encoding\n    47→- State minimization (merge equivalent states)\n    48→- Logic minimization (reduce AND gates via BDD or ABC)\n    49→- Re-encoding with fewer latches\n    50→\n    51→## Benchmark landscape\n    52→\n    53→- 1586 instances from SYNTCOMP 2025 LTL selection\n    54→- ~238 known realizable, ~111 known unrealizable, ~1237 unknown status\n    55→- ~259 instances have reference solution sizes (ref_size)\n    56→- Families include: amba, load_balancer, arbiter, collector, lift, ltl2dba, ltl2dpa, detector, etc.\n    57→\n    58→## Instance family insights\n    59→\n    60→(To be filled as experiments reveal patterns)\n    61→\n    62→## Approach selection guide\n    63→\n    64→(To be filled based on experimental results. Key factors: n_inputs, n_outputs, spec structure, family)\n    65→\n    66→## Technique discoveries\n    67→\n    68→(To be filled as new techniques are discovered and validated)\n    69→\n    70→## Approaches that DON'T work\n    71→\n    72→(To be filled with failed approaches and why they failed)\n    73→\n    74→## Current status\n    75→\n    76→(To be updated with solve counts, quality metrics, and next priorities)\n    77→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6882dd44-b12a-40ea-abce-8556d98170ba","uuid":"f566d2af-d87a-4409-82e1-84dc3591a8a1","timestamp":"2026-03-19T18:35:25.202Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/samkouteili/yale/rose/autosynt/expert.md","content":"# LTL Reactive Synthesis Expert Knowledge\n\n## Problem overview\n\n**Reactive synthesis**: given an LTL specification over input and output signals, construct a controller (Mealy/Moore machine) that satisfies the spec for ALL possible input sequences, or determine that no such controller exists (unrealizable).\n\n**Dual optimization goal**:\n1. Determine realizability status for as many instances as possible (both realizable and unrealizable count)\n2. For realizable instances, minimize AND gate count in the AIGER circuit encoding\n\n## Available primitives\n\n| Tool | Purpose | Analog in MaxSAT |\n|------|---------|-------------------|\n| `syfco` | Parse TLSF files → LTL formula, inputs, outputs | wcnf_parser |\n| `ltl2tgba` / `autfilt` | LTL → automaton conversion, automaton manipulation | SAT solver call |\n| PySAT + CaDiCaL | SAT encoding for bounded synthesis | Core-guided MaxSAT |\n| `ltlsynt` | Complete synthesis tool (baseline to beat) | RC2 |\n| Custom Python | Game solving, strategy extraction, circuit optimization | Local search |\n\n## Key algorithmic approaches\n\n### 1. Automaton-based pipeline (standard approach)\n1. Parse TLSF → LTL formula + I/O signals\n2. Convert LTL to universal co-Büchi automaton (UCW) or deterministic parity automaton (DPA)\n3. Build 2-player parity game from automaton\n4. Solve game (Zielonka's algorithm)\n5. Extract winning strategy → Mealy machine → AIGER circuit\n\n### 2. Bounded synthesis (SAT-based)\n- Encode \"exists k-state controller satisfying spec?\" as SAT\n- Try k = 1, 2, 4, 8, ... until SAT or timeout\n- Directly finds minimal-state controllers\n- Best for small specs where automaton blows up\n\n### 3. GR(1) fragment\n- Specs of form (∧ GF(a_i)) → (∧ GF(b_j)) with safety/justice conditions\n- Polynomial-time synthesis (no automaton construction needed)\n- Many SYNTCOMP instances are GR(1) — identify and exploit this\n\n### 4. Safety reduction\n- Some liveness specs can be reduced to safety via bounded lookahead\n- Safety games are simpler (reachability/safety, no parity conditions)\n\n### 5. Circuit minimization\n- After finding a correct controller, minimize the AIGER encoding\n- State minimization (merge equivalent states)\n- Logic minimization (reduce AND gates via BDD or ABC)\n- Re-encoding with fewer latches\n\n## Benchmark landscape\n\n- 1586 instances from SYNTCOMP 2025 LTL selection\n- ~238 known realizable, ~111 known unrealizable, ~1237 unknown status\n- ~259 instances have reference solution sizes (ref_size)\n- Families include: amba, load_balancer, arbiter, collector, lift, ltl2dba, ltl2dpa, detector, etc.\n\n## Instance family insights\n\n(To be filled as experiments reveal patterns)\n\n## Approach selection guide\n\n(To be filled based on experimental results. Key factors: n_inputs, n_outputs, spec structure, family)\n\n## Technique discoveries\n\n(To be filled as new techniques are discovered and validated)\n\n## Approaches that DON'T work\n\n(To be filled with failed approaches and why they failed)\n\n## Current status\n\n(To be updated with solve counts, quality metrics, and next priorities)\n","numLines":77,"startLine":1,"totalLines":77}}}
