{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01ECpoKGwRpwjwzhbkTjtYHp","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# LTL Reactive Synthesis Expert Knowledge\n     2→\n     3→## Problem overview\n     4→\n     5→**Reactive synthesis**: given an LTL specification over input and output signals, construct a controller (Mealy/Moore machine) that satisfies the spec for ALL possible input sequences, or determine that no such controller exists (unrealizable).\n     6→\n     7→**Dual optimization goal**:\n     8→1. Determine realizability status for as many instances as possible (both realizable and unrealizable count)\n     9→2. For realizable instances, minimize AND gate count in the AIGER circuit encoding\n    10→\n    11→## Available primitives\n    12→\n    13→| Tool | Purpose | Analog in MaxSAT |\n    14→|------|---------|-------------------|\n    15→| `syfco` | Parse TLSF files → LTL formula, inputs, outputs | wcnf_parser |\n    16→| `ltl2tgba` / `autfilt` | LTL → automaton conversion, automaton manipulation | SAT solver call |\n    17→| PySAT + CaDiCaL | SAT encoding for bounded synthesis | Core-guided MaxSAT |\n    18→| `ltlsynt` | Complete synthesis tool (baseline to beat) | RC2 |\n    19→| Custom Python | Game solving, strategy extraction, circuit optimization | Local search |\n    20→\n    21→## Key algorithmic approaches\n    22→\n    23→### 1. Automaton-based pipeline (standard approach)\n    24→1. Parse TLSF → LTL formula + I/O signals\n    25→2. Convert LTL to universal co-Büchi automaton (UCW) or deterministic parity automaton (DPA)\n    26→3. Build 2-player parity game from automaton\n    27→4. Solve game (Zielonka's algorithm)\n    28→5. Extract winning strategy → Mealy machine → AIGER circuit\n    29→\n    30→### 2. Bounded synthesis (SAT-based)\n    31→- Encode \"exists k-state controller satisfying spec?\" as SAT\n    32→- Try k = 1, 2, 4, 8, ... until SAT or timeout\n    33→- Directly finds minimal-state controllers\n    34→- Best for small specs where automaton blows up\n    35→\n    36→### 3. GR(1) fragment\n    37→- Specs of form (∧ GF(a_i)) → (∧ GF(b_j)) with safety/justice conditions\n    38→- Polynomial-time synthesis (no automaton construction needed)\n    39→- Many SYNTCOMP instances are GR(1) — identify and exploit this\n    40→\n    41→### 4. Safety reduction\n    42→- Some liveness specs can be reduced to safety via bounded lookahead\n    43→- Safety games are simpler (reachability/safety, no parity conditions)\n    44→\n    45→### 5. Circuit minimization\n    46→- After finding a correct controller, minimize the AIGER encoding\n    47→- State minimization (merge equivalent states)\n    48→- Logic minimization (reduce AND gates via BDD or ABC)\n    49→- Re-encoding with fewer latches\n    50→\n    51→## Benchmark landscape\n    52→\n    53→- 1586 instances from SYNTCOMP 2025 LTL selection\n    54→- ~238 known realizable, ~111 known unrealizable, ~1237 unknown status\n    55→- ~259 instances have reference solution sizes (ref_size)\n    56→- Families include: amba, load_balancer, arbiter, collector, lift, ltl2dba, ltl2dpa, detector, etc.\n    57→\n    58→## Instance family insights\n    59→\n    60→(To be filled as experiments reveal patterns)\n    61→\n    62→## Approach selection guide\n    63→\n    64→(To be filled based on experimental results. Key factors: n_inputs, n_outputs, spec structure, family)\n    65→\n    66→## Technique discoveries\n    67→\n    68→(To be filled as new techniques are discovered and validated)\n    69→\n    70→## Approaches that DON'T work\n    71→\n    72→(To be filled with failed approaches and why they failed)\n    73→\n    74→## Current status\n    75→\n    76→(To be updated with solve counts, quality metrics, and next priorities)\n    77→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6882dd44-b12a-40ea-abce-8556d98170ba","uuid":"fa3f50b9-968d-42d4-86d7-d1751889c595","timestamp":"2026-03-19T20:00:39.228Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/samkouteili/yale/rose/autosynt/expert.md","content":"# LTL Reactive Synthesis Expert Knowledge\n\n## Problem overview\n\n**Reactive synthesis**: given an LTL specification over input and output signals, construct a controller (Mealy/Moore machine) that satisfies the spec for ALL possible input sequences, or determine that no such controller exists (unrealizable).\n\n**Dual optimization goal**:\n1. Determine realizability status for as many instances as possible (both realizable and unrealizable count)\n2. For realizable instances, minimize AND gate count in the AIGER circuit encoding\n\n## Available primitives\n\n| Tool | Purpose | Analog in MaxSAT |\n|------|---------|-------------------|\n| `syfco` | Parse TLSF files → LTL formula, inputs, outputs | wcnf_parser |\n| `ltl2tgba` / `autfilt` | LTL → automaton conversion, automaton manipulation | SAT solver call |\n| PySAT + CaDiCaL | SAT encoding for bounded synthesis | Core-guided MaxSAT |\n| `ltlsynt` | Complete synthesis tool (baseline to beat) | RC2 |\n| Custom Python | Game solving, strategy extraction, circuit optimization | Local search |\n\n## Key algorithmic approaches\n\n### 1. Automaton-based pipeline (standard approach)\n1. Parse TLSF → LTL formula + I/O signals\n2. Convert LTL to universal co-Büchi automaton (UCW) or deterministic parity automaton (DPA)\n3. Build 2-player parity game from automaton\n4. Solve game (Zielonka's algorithm)\n5. Extract winning strategy → Mealy machine → AIGER circuit\n\n### 2. Bounded synthesis (SAT-based)\n- Encode \"exists k-state controller satisfying spec?\" as SAT\n- Try k = 1, 2, 4, 8, ... until SAT or timeout\n- Directly finds minimal-state controllers\n- Best for small specs where automaton blows up\n\n### 3. GR(1) fragment\n- Specs of form (∧ GF(a_i)) → (∧ GF(b_j)) with safety/justice conditions\n- Polynomial-time synthesis (no automaton construction needed)\n- Many SYNTCOMP instances are GR(1) — identify and exploit this\n\n### 4. Safety reduction\n- Some liveness specs can be reduced to safety via bounded lookahead\n- Safety games are simpler (reachability/safety, no parity conditions)\n\n### 5. Circuit minimization\n- After finding a correct controller, minimize the AIGER encoding\n- State minimization (merge equivalent states)\n- Logic minimization (reduce AND gates via BDD or ABC)\n- Re-encoding with fewer latches\n\n## Benchmark landscape\n\n- 1586 instances from SYNTCOMP 2025 LTL selection\n- ~238 known realizable, ~111 known unrealizable, ~1237 unknown status\n- ~259 instances have reference solution sizes (ref_size)\n- Families include: amba, load_balancer, arbiter, collector, lift, ltl2dba, ltl2dpa, detector, etc.\n\n## Instance family insights\n\n(To be filled as experiments reveal patterns)\n\n## Approach selection guide\n\n(To be filled based on experimental results. Key factors: n_inputs, n_outputs, spec structure, family)\n\n## Technique discoveries\n\n(To be filled as new techniques are discovered and validated)\n\n## Approaches that DON'T work\n\n(To be filled with failed approaches and why they failed)\n\n## Current status\n\n(To be updated with solve counts, quality metrics, and next priorities)\n","numLines":77,"startLine":1,"totalLines":77}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01SG2qAX5kyfTM2pxohhK1UH","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_015zAos3Y2JG1AqHbVF36Lmj","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/Users/samkouteili/yale/rose/autosynt/expert.md","content":"# LTL Reactive Synthesis Expert Knowledge\n\n## Problem overview\n\n**Reactive synthesis**: given an LTL specification over input and output signals, construct a controller (Mealy/Moore machine) that satisfies the spec for ALL possible input sequences, or determine that no such controller exists (unrealizable).\n\n**Dual optimization goal**:\n1. Determine realizability status for as many instances as possible (both realizable and unrealizable count)\n2. For realizable instances, minimize AND gate count in the AIGER circuit encoding\n\n## Available primitives\n\n| Tool | Purpose | Notes |\n|------|---------|-------|\n| `syfco` | Parse TLSF files → LTL formula, inputs, outputs | Can't handle LTLf \"strong next\" operator |\n| `ltlsynt` | Complete synthesis tool (most effective) | Has many algorithm/option combos |\n| `spot` Python API | `ltl_to_game` → `solve_game` → AIGER | Available via `/opt/homebrew/bin/python3.14` |\n| `ltl2tgba` / `autfilt` | LTL → automaton conversion | Lower-level building blocks |\n| PySAT + CaDiCaL | SAT encoding for bounded synthesis | Implementation incomplete |\n\n## Key algorithmic approaches\n\n### 1. ltlsynt (most effective for breadth)\n- `ltlsynt --tlsf=FILE --aiger --decompose=yes` is the single most effective command\n- **Algorithm options**: `--algo=sd|ds|ps|lar|acd` — different algorithms solve different instances\n  - `sd` (split-determinize): best for many Spectra/smart-home benchmarks\n  - `ds` (determinize-split): complements sd, sometimes faster\n  - `lar` (default): good general-purpose, handles large automata\n  - `ps` (parity-split): rarely best but occasionally works where others fail\n  - `acd`: alternative to lar, similar performance\n- **Key flag**: `--decompose=yes` breaks spec into output-disjoint subproblems — CRITICAL for multi-output specs\n- **Simplification**: `--simplify=bisim|bwoa|sat|bisim-sat|bwoa-sat` — default `bwoa` usually best\n- **AIGER encoding**: `--aiger=both+ud+dc` tries multiple encodings and picks smallest\n\n### 2. Spot Python API (good for unrealizability + small instances)\nPipeline: `spot.formula()` → `spot.ltl_to_game(f, outputs)` → `spot.solve_game(arena)` → `spot.solved_game_to_split_mealy()` → `spot.print_aiger()`\n\n**Mealy optimization strategies** (try all, pick smallest):\n- `solved_game_to_split_mealy` (default, fast)\n- `simplify_mealy_here` with `minimize_lvl=2` or `3`\n- `minimize_mealy` (unsplit, minimizes states)\n- AIGER encodings: \"isop\", \"ite\", \"both+dc\", \"both+ud+dc\"\n\n### 3. Re-optimization strategy (CRITICAL for circuit quality)\nFor instances already solved by spot_game, re-running with ltlsynt often produces **dramatically** smaller circuits:\n- Coffee_235467da: 107,363 → 339 gates (99.7% reduction!)\n- lazy_shades_problem: 51,554 → 3 gates\n- lift_pb_5: 19,972 → 1,374 gates\n- Many instances reduced from thousands to single-digit gates\nThe key insight: ltlsynt's `--decompose` + different algorithms explore very different solution spaces.\n\n### 4. Family probing strategy (efficient for breadth)\nInstead of trying all instances, test ONE instance per unsolved family first. If a family is tractable, batch-solve the rest. This identified 25+ tractable families in one pass.\n\n## Benchmark landscape\n\n- 1586 instances from SYNTCOMP 2025 LTL selection\n- ~238 known realizable, ~111 known unrealizable, ~1237 unknown status\n- Families include: amba, load_balancer, arbiter, collector, lift, ltl2dba, ltl2dpa, Spectra smart-home, etc.\n\n## Instance family insights\n\n### Instantly solvable (ltlsynt --decompose, <1s)\n- **simple_arbiter_unreal1**: all 53 instances solved instantly. Decomposition is key.\n- **prioritized_arbiter_unreal1/2**: most solved instantly with decompose\n- **simple_arbiter_unreal2**: solved with decompose\n- **gf-unreal family**: individual instances, each solved in <1s\n- **F-G-contradiction**: solved with decompose\n- **g-unreal**: most solved with decompose in <1s\n\n### Solvable with moderate effort (1-30s)\n- **ltl2dba_C2/E/Q/U1/theta**: realizable instances up to ~15 signals\n- **lift, lift_gr1, lift_unary_enc**: realizable, moderate circuits\n- **Spectra smart-home** (Lights, Coffee, Alarm, Shades, etc.): realizable, large circuits from spot but small from ltlsynt\n- **amba_decomposed_arbiter/encode**: solvable with decompose\n- **collector_v1/v3**: realizable, large game states\n\n### Hard (>60s or intractable)\n- **full_arbiter_unreal1**: X-nesting depth (u parameter) causes exponential game construction time. u≤18 works (~22s), u>20 intractable\n- **round_robin_arbiter_unreal1**: similar to full_arbiter_unreal1, 3i/3o but deep nesting\n- **numeric**: huge formulas (29K+ chars), no ltlsynt algorithm works in 30s\n- **finding_nemo**: LTLf benchmarks using \"strong next\" operator, syfco can't parse\n- **amba_decomposed_lock**: large signal counts (12-402), intractable\n- **mux**: large signal counts (12-209)\n- **shift**: up to 1000 signals, infeasible\n\n## Approach selection guide\n\n| Signals | Family type | Best approach |\n|---------|-------------|---------------|\n| ≤8 | Any unreal | ltlsynt --decompose (try sd, ds, lar) |\n| ≤15 | Most families | ltlsynt --decompose + multiple algos |\n| ≤15 | Arbiter unreal (high params) | spot game (slow but works if game builds in time) |\n| 15-25 | Spectra/smart-home | ltlsynt-sd+decompose (produces smallest circuits) |\n| 15-25 | AMBA decomposed | ltlsynt+decompose |\n| >25 | Any | Likely intractable with current tools |\n\n**For circuit quality**: Always re-optimize spot_game solutions with ltlsynt --algo=sd --decompose=yes --aiger=both+ud+dc\n\n## Approaches that DON'T work\n\n- **Spot game on high-parameter arbiters**: X^u nesting with u>20 causes game construction to exceed any reasonable timeout (exponential in u)\n- **Bounded synthesis (current implementation)**: SAT encoding is incomplete, doesn't properly encode automaton transitions\n- **ltlsynt without --decompose**: Dramatically slower on multi-output specs\n- **Single algorithm**: No single ltlsynt algorithm dominates — sd, ds, lar each win on different instances\n- **Python subprocess nesting**: Running python3.14 via subprocess from python3.14 is unreliable for background tasks (output buffering issues)\n- **syfco on LTLf specs**: \"strong next\" operator not supported\n\n## Current status\n\n**845 solved / 1586 total** (380 realizable, 465 unrealizable) = 53.3%\n\n**Next priorities**:\n1. Implement proper bounded synthesis (SAT-based) for small instances where both ltlsynt and spot time out\n2. Build custom approach for parametric arbiter_unreal families (exploit formula structure rather than building full game)\n3. Handle LTLf instances (finding_nemo family) — need direct LTLf synthesis\n4. Try `ltl2tgba` formula simplification before synthesis for borderline instances\n5. Explore ABC/yosys for post-synthesis circuit optimization (not currently installed)\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1189,"cache_read_input_tokens":143925,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1189},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6882dd44-b12a-40ea-abce-8556d98170ba","uuid":"44821bd0-9a68-448c-a1b2-8ec09de736f2"}
